nsition are familiar to us all, whatever our age, gender, ethnicity or social status – namely, the impossibility of calculating what one may lose in leaving a settled life or home place; what one may gain by risking oneself in an alien environment; the difficulty of striking a balance between personal fulfillment and the moral claims of kinship; and the struggle to know the difference between ‘concrete’ and ‘abstract’ utopias (the first reasonable and worth pursuing; the second hopelessly unattainable).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aEthicsxAnthropological aspects. 0aHuman comfort. 0aImmigrantsvCross-cultural studies. 0aWell-being. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aamerica.  aamsterdam.  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  abiographical.  aboston.  aburkina faso migrant.  acontemporary migration.  acopenhagen.  acultural anthropology.  adiscussion books.  aethical dilemmas.  aethics.  aeurope.  aglobal south.  aimmigrant experiences.  alife changes.  alife experiences.  amexican migrant.  amigration studies.  amigration.  amodern life.  anonfiction.  aphenomenological accounts.  aphilosophy.  asocial historians.  asocial science.  augandan migrant.  awell being.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027672740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095681040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956810423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956810/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY